Introduction¶

In the past few decades, the world has been going green. The use of renewable energy sources has been on the rise and many countries have been trying to reduce their carbon footprint. In 2015, 16% of the total global electricity production was from renewable sources. This project is investigating the impact of the renewable energy production on Total GDP, Non-Renewable Energy Consumption and the CO2 Emissions across Countries using Gapminder World Data. Since the renewable energy production (especially hydropower) datasets were not updated from 2011 and some are not found, we used International Renewable Energy Agency (IRENA) updated datasets to complete this project. The investigation and results in this report are broken into three sections, which are described below. Each section will contain the individual datasets chosen and used, in addition to the questions raised to explore this section.

The Effect of Renewable Energy Production on Total GDP across Countries.¶

Renewable energy is not just about reducing our environmental footprint but also about improving our economy. The renewable energy market has become a significant segment of energy production which may or may not affect the total GDP. In this section, we analyze the below mentioned dataset to clarify different questions concerning the top ten countries in terms of total GDP and how total GDP varies with renewable energy production.

Datasets¶

  • IRENA

    • Total Renewable Production

  • Gapminder World

    • Economy
      • Total GDP (USD, inflation-adjusted)

Questions¶

  1. Which five countries have the highest mean renewable energy generation from 2000 to 2020?
  2. Which five countries have the greatest Total GDP from 2000 to 2020?
  3. What are the distributions of the renewable energy production and total GDP from 2000 to 2020?
  4. Does the generation of renewable energy affect countries' total GDP?
  5. What are the trends in renewable energy production in countries with the largest total GDP?

The Effect of Renewable Energy Production on Non-Renewable Energy Consumption across Countries.¶

The effect of green energy production on non-renewable energy consumption across countries has been the subject of ongoing debate for many years. While supporters of renewable energy sources maintain that the transition to renewables will help decrease our dependence on fossil fuels, opponents argue that the required infrastructure changes would be too costly and time-consuming. In this section, we investigate the datasets provided below to answer several questions concerning the key contributor countries to non-renewable energy consumption (i.e., oil and coal) and whether there is a relationship between producing green energy and reducing non-renewable energy consumption.

Datasets¶

  • IRENA

    • Total Renewable Production

  • Gapminder World

    • Energy
      • Oil Consumption Total
      • Coal Consumption Total

Questions¶

  1. Which five countries consumed the most non-renewable energy between 2000 and 2019?
  2. What are the distributions of total renewable energy production and total non-renewable energy consumption from 2000 to 2019?
  3. Does the generation of renewable energy diminish the consumption of non-renewable energy?
  4. What are the trends in renewable energy production in the top five non-renewable energy consuming countries?

The Effect of Renewable Energy Production on CO2 Emissions across Countries.¶

The production of renewable energy results in lower carbon dioxide emissions when compared to traditional forms of energy generation. This section analyzes the datasets provided below to address various questions about the major contributor countries to renewable energy production and whether there is a link between generating renewable energy and lowering CO2 emissions.

Datasets¶

  • IRENA

    • Total Renewable Production

  • Gapminder World

    • Environment
      • CO2 Emission Yearly

Questions¶

  1. Which five countries have the highest mean annual CO2 emissions between 2000 and 2018?
  2. What are the distributions of total renewable energy production and total CO2 emissions from 2000 to 2018?
  3. Does the production of renewable energy reduce CO2 emissions?
  4. What are the trends in renewable energy production and CO2 emissions in the top five countries?

General Properties¶

We inspected both the renewable energy and total GDP dataframes, and we found out the following:

   A. Total Renewable Energy Production Dataset

  1. Total Renewable Energy Production dataset df_renewable has total of 24 columns and 247 rows.
  2. The first column is named Region/country/area as it contains not only countries from which the data was collected, but continents names with total values of its countries.
  3. The second column is named Technology and it has only one value for all rows which is Total renewable energy.
  4. From the third to the last columns are years from 2000 to 2021.
  5. All columns' data type are object.

   B. Total GDP Dataset

  1. Total GDP dataset df_gdp has total of 62 columns and 207 rows.
  2. The first column is named country and it includes country names from which the data was collected.
  3. The remaining columns are years from 1960 to 2020.
  4. All columns' data type are also object.

Step 4: Changing year columns data type¶

While inspecting the df gdp data earlier, we noticed that some numbers contain various strings such as K,M,B,and TR. These letters stand in for thousands, millions, billions, and trillions of dollars, which are values that may be used to modify the data type on the year columns. To modify the data type, just substitute any letter with the corresponding zeros with the following code.

In [22]:
# Change data type to float in df_gdp
for key, val in df_gdp.items():
    df_gdp[key] = df_gdp[key].replace({'k':'*1e3', 'M':'*1e6', 'B': '*1e9', 'TR': '*1e12'}, regex = True).map(pd.eval).astype(float)

Now that we finished cleaning df_renewable and df_gdp dataframes, it is time to merge them, and before that we need to delete all the countries that is not in common between the two dataframes.

C. Merging the two dataframes¶

Merging the two dataframes into one will be impossible until all of the countries that are not shared by both dataframes are removed. To do that we will follow some steps

Step 1: Deleting un-shared country rows from df_renewable¶

we will first delete all the rows that contains countries in df_renewable and not found in df_gdp.

In [23]:
# Delete the rows with countries that are in `df_renewable` and not in `df_gdp` dataframe.
for c in df_renewable.index:
    try:
        if c not in df_gdp.index:
            df_renewable.drop(c, axis=0, inplace = True)
    except:
        continue

Step 11.5: Melting the renewable energy production data into vertical structure¶

In this step we first melt the data to be in a vertical structure, then we will sort the data values by country and year so that each country will appear in a row starting from 2000 till 2020. Finaly, we are going to reset the new data index to be in order. Doing all these steps will show its ressults when we start graphing the data.

In [39]:
# Changing the layout of the collected data from df_renewable_v1
df_renewable_v2 = df_renewable_v1.melt(id_vars = 'country'
                   , var_name = 'year'
                   , value_vars = list(df_renewable_v1.columns[1:])
                   , value_name = 'renewable_production')

# Sorting by country and year
df_renewable_v2.sort_values(by = ['country','year'], inplace=True)

# Reset the data index
df_renewable_v2.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

General Properties¶

We inspected both the new modified renewable energy, total coal consumption and total oil consumption dataframes, and we found out the following:

   A. Total Renewable Energy Production Dataset

  1. The updated total Renewable Energy Production dataset df_renewable has total of 21 columns and 231 rows.
  2. The first column is named country as it contains not only countries from which the data was collected, but continents names with total values of its countries.
  3. From the second to the last columns are years from 2000 to 2020.
  4. All columns' data type are float.

   B. Coal and Oil Consumption Total Datasets

  1. Coal Consumption Total dataset df_coal has total of 56 columns and 80 rows.
  2. The first column is named country and it includes country names from which the data was collected.
  3. The remaining columns are years from 1965 to 2019.
  4. All columns' data type are object.
  5. Oil Consumption Total dataset df_oil has the same structure of df_coal with total of 56 columns and 80 rows.

Step 4: Changing year columns data type¶

While inspecting the df_coal and df_oil data earlier, we noticed that some numbers contain various strings such as K,M, and B. These letters stand in for thousands, millions, and billions of tonnes, which are values that may be used to modify the data type on the year columns. To modify the data type, just substitute any letter with the corresponding zeros with the following code.

Step 4.1: Changing year columns data type in df_coal¶
In [66]:
# Change data type to float in df_coal

    df_coal[key] = df_coal[key].replace({'k':'*1e3', 'M':'*1e6', 'B': '*1e9'}, regex = True).map(pd.eval).astype(float)

General Properties¶

We inspected both the new modified renewable energy, total CO2 emissions dataframes, and we found out the following:

   A. Total Renewable Energy Production Dataset

  1. The updated total Renewable Energy Production dataset df_renewable has total of 21 columns and 231 rows.
  2. The first column is named country as it contains not only countries from which the data was collected, but continents names with total values of its countries.
  3. From the second to the last columns are years from 2000 to 2020.
  4. All columns' data type are float.

   B. CO2 Emission Yearly Datasets

  1. CO2 Emission Yearly dataset df_co2 has total of 269 columns and 232 rows.
  2. The first column is named country and it includes country names from which the data was collected.
  3. The remaining columns are years from 1751 to 2018.
  4. Only 5 columns have the type float and the rest has type object.

Step 4: Changing year columns data type¶

While inspecting the df_co2 data earlier, we noticed that some numbers contain various strings such as K, and M. These letters stand in for thousands, and millions of 1000 tonnes, which are values that may be used to modify the data type on the year columns. To modify the data type, just substitute any letter with the corresponding zeros with the following code.

In [105]:
# Change data type to float in df_co2
for key, val in df_co2.items():
    df_co2[key] = df_co2[key].replace({'k':'*1e3', 'M':'*1e6'}, regex = True).map(pd.eval).astype(float)

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Customized Plotting Functions¶

To avoid repetitive code, we created some cutomized plotting functions such as ticks(), plot_bar(), plot_twin_bar(), plot_hist() and plot_scatter() that will help us in plotting most of the graphs in the exploratory phase.

1. ticks() Function¶

This function just changes the tick on all graphs so that they are displayed clearly; it takes the largest number in any data and returns a letter, whether it is K, M, B, or TR instead of the multiple zeros that may confuse the reader. Furthermore, it returns the axis range with the steps between ticks in this axis. It is particularly useful in formatting the x-axis and y-axis of any graph, which is why it is included with the other functions.

In [129]:
def ticks(num):
    """
    provide ticks formats for plotting.

    Args:
        num - the max value in axis values
        
    Returns:
        some format for the y-axis format such as range and ticks labels
    """
    if num <= 1e6:
        letter = 'K'
        nearest = 1e3
        step = 0.5*1e5
        stop = (np.ceil(num/step)*step)+1
    elif num <= 1e9:
        letter = 'M'
        nearest = 1e6
        step = 1e6
        stop = (np.ceil(num/step)*step)+1    
    elif num <= 1e12:
        letter = 'B'
        nearest = 1e9
        step = 0.5*1e9
        stop = (np.ceil(num/step)*step)+1
    elif num <= 1e15:
        letter = 'TR'
        nearest = 1e12
        step = 2*1e12
        stop = (np.ceil(num/step)*step)+1
    
    return [letter, nearest, step, stop]

2. plot_bar Function¶

This function creates a bar chart from a set of data. It requires the following four arguments:

  • df --> the dataframe that will be used in the graph

  • x_axis --> the column that will be plotted in the x-axis

  • y_axis --> the column that will be plotted in the y-axis

  • labels --> list of graph title, label on x axis, label on y-axis
    • </ul> After putting the right arguments, the function will return a professionally plotted bar chart with a title, x and y labels, and formatted ticks.

In [130]:
def plot_bar(df, x_axis, y_axis, labels):
    
    """
    Plot a bar chart for specific data.

    Args:
        df     - the dataframe that will be used in the graph
        x_axis - the column that will be plotted in the x-axis
        y_axis - the column that will be plotted in the y-axis
        labels - list of graph title, label on x axis, label on y-axis
        
    Returns:
        A graph for the selected data.
    """

    plt.subplots(figsize=(8,5))
    
    plt.bar(df[x_axis], df[y_axis])
    
    plt.title(labels['title'], fontsize=20, fontweight='bold')
    
    plt.xlabel(labels['xlabel'], fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
    plt.xticks(fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
    
    y_ticks = ticks(df[y_axis].max())
    plt.ylabel(labels['ylabel'], fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
    plt.yticks(np.arange(0,y_ticks[-1],y_ticks[-2]), fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
    
    plt.gca().set_yticklabels(['{:1.2f} {}'.format(x/y_ticks[1], y_ticks[0])
                               for x in np.arange(0,y_ticks[-1],y_ticks[-2])]);

3. plot_twin_bar Function¶

This function creates a twin bar chart from a set of data. It requires the following five arguments:

  • df --> the dataframe that will be used in the graph

  • x_axis --> the column that will be plotted in the x-axis

  • y_axis1 --> the column that will be plotted in the first y-axis

  • y_axis2 --> the column that will be plotted in the second y-axis

  • labels --> list of graph title, label on x axis, label on y-axis1 and y-axis2
    • </ul> After putting the right arguments, the function will return a professionally plotted twin bar chart with a title, x and y labels, and formatted ticks.

In [131]:
def plot_twin_bar(df, x_axis, y_axis1, y_axis2, labels):
    
    """
    Plot a twin bar chart for specific data.

    Args:
        df     - the dataframe that will be used in the graph
        x_axis - the column that will be plotted in the x-axis
        y_axis1 - the column that will be plotted in the first y-axis
        y_axis2 - the column that will be plotted in the second y-axis
        labels - list of graph title, label on x axis, label on y-axis1 and y-axis2
        
    Returns:
        A twin bar graph for the selected data.
    """    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(16,10))
    
    x1 = ax.bar(df[x_axis]-0.2, df[y_axis1], width=0.4)
    
    y_ticks1 = ticks(df[y_axis1].max())
    ax.set_ylabel(labels['ylabel1'], fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
    ax.set_yticks(np.arange(0,y_ticks1[-1], y_ticks1[-2]), fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')
    ax.set_yticklabels(['{:1.1f} {}'.format(x/y_ticks1[1], y_ticks1[0]) for x in np.arange(0,y_ticks1[-1], y_ticks1[-2])])

    ax1 = ax.twinx()

    
    x2 = ax1.bar(df[x_axis]+0.2, df[y_axis2], color ='red', width=0.4)

    y_ticks2 = ticks(df[y_axis2].max())
    ax1.set_ylabel(labels['ylabel2'], fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
    ax1.set_yticks(np.arange(0,y_ticks2[-1], y_ticks2[-2]), fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')
    ax1.set_yticklabels(['{:1.1f} {}'.format(x/y_ticks2[1], y_ticks2[0]) for x in np.arange(0,y_ticks2[-1], y_ticks2[-2])])

    # Putting title, x labels and legend
    plt.title(labels['title'], fontsize=20, fontweight='bold')

    ax.set_xlabel(labels['xlabel'], fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
    ax.set_xticks(df[x_axis], fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
    
    plt.legend(handles = [x1, x2]
               , labels=[y_axis1, y_axis2]
               , loc = 'upper left'
               , fontsize = 14);

4. plot_hist Function¶

This function creates a histogram from a set of data. It requires the following two arguments:

  • x_axis --> the column that will be plotted in the x-axis

  • labels --> list of graph title, label on x axis, label on y-axis
    • </ul> After putting the right arguments, the function will return a professionally plotted histogram with a title, x and y labels, and formatted ticks.

In [132]:
def plot_hist(x_axis, labels):
    
    """
    Plot a histogram for specific data.

    Args:
        x_axis - the column that will be plotted in the x-axis
        labels - list of graph title, label on x axis, label on y-axis
        
    Returns:
        A graph for the selected data.
    """ 
    plt.subplots(figsize=(15,5))
    sns.histplot(x_axis)
    
    plt.title(labels['title'], fontsize=20, fontweight='bold')
    
    x_ticks = ticks(x_axis.max())
    plt.xlabel(labels['xlabel'], fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
    plt.xticks(np.arange(0,x_ticks[-1],x_ticks[-2]), fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
    
    plt.gca().set_xticklabels(['{:1.2f} {}'.format(x/x_ticks[1], x_ticks[0])
                               for x in np.arange(0,x_ticks[-1],x_ticks[-2])])
    
    
    plt.ylabel(labels['ylabel'], fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
    plt.yticks(fontsize=12, fontweight='bold');

5. plot_scatter Function¶

This function creates a scatter graph from a set of data. It requires the following three arguments:

  • x_axis --> the column that will be plotted in the x-axis

  • y_axis --> the column that will be plotted in the y-axis

  • labels --> list of graph title, label on x axis, label on y-axis
    • </ul> After putting the right arguments, the function will return a professionally plotted scattered graph with a title, x and y labels, and formatted ticks.

In [133]:
def plot_scatter(x_axis, y_axis, labels):
    
    """
    Plot a scatter graph for specific data.

    Args:
        x_axis - the column that will be plotted in the x-axis
        y_axis - the column that will be plotted in the y-axis
        labels - list of graph title, label on x axis, label on y-axis
        
    Returns:
        A graph for the selected data.
    """ 
    plt.subplots(figsize=(15,5))
    sns.regplot(x = x_axis, y = y_axis, line_kws={"color": "red"}, ci=None)
    
    plt.title(labels['title'], fontsize=20, fontweight='bold')
    
    x_ticks = ticks(x_axis.max())
    plt.xlabel(labels['xlabel'], fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
    plt.xticks(np.arange(0,x_ticks[-1],x_ticks[-2]), fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
    
    plt.gca().set_xticklabels(['{:1.2f} {}'.format(x/x_ticks[1], x_ticks[0])
                               for x in np.arange(0,x_ticks[-1],x_ticks[-2])])
    
    y_ticks = ticks(y_axis.max())
    plt.ylabel(labels['ylabel'], fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
    plt.yticks(np.arange(0,y_ticks[-1],y_ticks[-2]), fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')
    
    plt.gca().set_yticklabels(['{:1.2f} {}'.format(x/y_ticks[1], y_ticks[0])
                               for x in np.arange(0,y_ticks[-1],y_ticks[-2])]);

Question 1: Which five countries have the highest mean renewable energy generation from 2000 to 2020?¶

As previously revealed during the data cleaning process, the five largest producers of renewable energy from 2000 to 2020 were China, United States, Brazil, Canada, and Germany.

Let's graph them in a bar chart to see the differences in renewable energy production between these five countries.

We will plot high_mean_renewable_gdp dataframe in this bar chart using plot_bar function defined before which takes df, x_axis, y_axis and labels as arrguments.

The bar chart shows the following:

  • China has been the highest in total annual renewable energy production with 322K MW.
  • In the second place comes the United states with 155K MW, wich is almost half the total mean of renewable energy production for China.
  • Brazil was in the third place with 96K MW, which is almost 60% of what the united states produce, and only 30% of what China produce.
  • As for Canada and Germany, they placed in the forth and fifth places respectively.


In conclusion, it is clear from the chart that there is an enormous discrepancy between these five nations, with China and the United States leading the way and Germany trailing behind.

Conclusions¶

The Effect of Renewable Energy Production on Total GDP¶

    From 2000 to 2020, China and the United States lead in total renewable energy production, followed by Brazil, Canada, and Japan, whereas the United States leads in annual mean total GDP, followed by China, Japan, Germany, and the United Kingdom.
    This section's analysis shows a direct relationship between expanding renewable energy production and boosting overall GDP. Except for 2020, which forecasts a 5% fall in overall GDP in most nations despite increased renewable energy production. The impact of the COVID-19 pandemic is responsible for the reduction in global total GDPs.
    China was the only exception, with its overall GDP increasing by around 2%, proving China's triumph over all other nations in mitigating the outbreak's impact.
    To summarise, all of the metrics examined demonstrated that increasing total renewable energy production had a positive influence on raising total GDP by reducing total non-renewable fuel consumption after eliminating the year 2020.

The Effect of Renewable Energy Production on Non-renewable Energy Consumption¶

    As in the preceding section, China and the United States lead in total renewable energy production, followed by Brazil, Canada, and Japan, while China and the United States also lead in non-renewable energy consumption, followed by India, Japan, and Russia.
    With the exception of Russia and Japan, the same nations with the greatest mean annual CO2 emissions were ranked in the same order with the highest non-renewable fuel usage. This exception illustrates that, while using more non-renewable fuels, Japan invests more in lowering emissions than Russia.
    According to this analysis, producing renewable energy will significantly reduce non-renewable energy use. In reality, the analysis in this section anticipated that the reason producing renewable energy reduces CO2 emissions is that it reduces non-renewable energy consumption, which is the source of the majority of CO2 emissions.
    From 2011 to 2019, the exponential growth in renewable energy generation in China halted the exponential rise in non-renewable energy consumption. In the United States, on the other hand, the exponential rise in renewable energy production lowered overall non-renewable energy demand by around 25%.
    In terms of overall non-renewable energy consumption, China's annual consumption nearly tripled from 2000 to 2019, however the growth has come to a halt from 2011 to 2019 due to increased renewable energy production, while in the case of the United States, consumption has been cut by roughly 25.
    To summarise, renewable energy production has a favourable influence on dramatically lowering total use of non-renewable fuels, which decreases CO2 emissions and helps to keep our world clean.

The Effect of Renewable Energy Production on CO2 Emissions¶

    From 2000 to 2018, China and the United States had the highest annual mean renewable energy production and CO2 emissions. In terms of high annual mean renewable energy production, these two countries were followed by Brazil, Canada, and Germany, and in terms of high annual mean CO2 emissions, India, Russia, and Japan.
    We discovered that producing renewable energy had a beneficial impact on lowering CO2 emissions after exploring and visualising data from China and the United States about renewable energy production and CO2 emissions.
    From 2000 to 2018, the production of renewable energy in China increased by almost 700 percent, and in the United States by around 200 percent, whereas the rest of the world countries had a limited or flat rise in renewable energy production.
    Regarding CO2 emissions, China quadrupled its emissions from 2000 to 2011, and then maintained its emissions level from 2011 to 2018 as a result of increased renewable energy production. In comparison, the United States was able to not only maintain a fairly level line with no rise in annual CO2 emissions, but also reduce omissions by around 15%. Unlike China and the United States, which invested in renewable energy to reduce CO2 emissions, India did not show any significant increase in renewable energy production, and as a result, it did not maintain or reduce CO2 emissions over time, but instead increased by nearly 300 percent to become the highest third country in CO2 emissions.
    In conclusion, all of the metrics examined demonstrated that increasing total renewable energy production had a negative influence on CO2 emissions, which will assist to preserve the world's ecology and keep the planet cleaner.

Limitations¶

    The three analyses in this report on the influence of renewable energy production on CO2 emissions, non-renewable energy consumption, and total GDP are not conclusive since they do not cover all of the countries in the glope.
    The research was conducted for just the top five countries in each category and from 2000 to 2018 in the case of CO2 emissions, from 2000 to 2019 in the case of non-renewable energy production, and from 2000 to 2020 in the case of GDP, which is insufficient to generate a final accurate conclusion.
    Furthermore, during the data cleaning phase, we decreased the sample size by excluding countries with any null values, and we further limited the selected sample by picking only the common countries in various datasets.
    In the case of non-renewable energy consumption, we exclusively analysed oil and coal usage only, ignoring other non-renewable fuels.
    In the case of Total GDP, we ignored other internal and external factors that may have an impact on total GDP, such as taxes, wages, interest rates, devaluation, and so on.
    All of these constraints prohibit us from making a definitive conclusion. Acquiring and analysing data for all countries and for more years would influence the final results of this report; additionally, adding more factors that may be affected by producing renewable energy will drive a more detailed report with a definitive conclusion; however, this report provides a foundation that will be expanded given larger quantities of data for all countries and for more years.
